some performance improvements--HG--nbranch : trunkn

Changed naked except statements to catch only subclasses of Exception.Naked except statements catch subclasses of BaseException whichncan occur anywhere (i.e. KeyboardInterrupt).nnUnexpected issues can occur when the exception happens during thenloading of a module. The python interpreter doesn't know about anmodule's failed load and does not remove it from sys.modules. Thisnis particularly a problem on AppEngine where python will think thenmodule is loaded but in fact the module load has failed.nnSee: http://code.google.com/p/googleappengine/issues/detail?id=1409nSigned-off-by: Armin Ronacher <armin.ronacher@active-4.com>n

Disallow f(x, y=1, z) and similar nonsensePython rejects such function definitions because it doesn't make muchnsense to have arguments with no default values after arguments withndefault values.nnJinja did allow them, but handled them improperly (associating thendefault value with the wrong argument).nnDue to how broken the current behavior is, it makes more sense to rejectntemplates containing such defintions instead of trying to handle themnproperly. Both cases are going to break existing code containing suchndefinitions, but besides the fact that possibly no such code exists itnis better to fail with a clear error than to silently change the valuesnof arguments.nnThis fixes #364n

Fix literal  characters at the end of a stringGiven a statement like `{% set sep = '' %}`, the syntax highlighter was considering the literal `''` to be a literal quote inside the string by matching `'` and thus highlighting the rest of the entire document as a string.rnrnThis change fixes that issue by adding some regex to ensure that an escaped quote is preceded by an uneven number of slashes (that is, `'''` would accept the literal string `'` without issues). A`` quoted string is modified the same way.

runtime: avoid assumption that all objects provide __call__Objects which are backed by native extensions do not providena __call__ attribute, but are none the less callable if thennative extension provides a 'tp_call' implementation.nnThe jinja2.runtime.Context.call method unconditionallynaccess the '__call__' attribute causing an exception to benraised if the object was a native extension method.nnA demo of the problem can be seen using PyGObject:nn  $ cat demo.pyn  #!/usr/bin/pythonnn  from gi.repository import Gion  from jinja2 import Environmentnn  f = Gio.File.new_for_path(/some/file.txt)n  print f.get_uri()nn  t = Environment().from_string({{f.get_uri()}})n  print t.render(f=f)nnWhich when run results innn $ ./demo.pyn file:///some/file.txtn Traceback (most recent call last):n   File ./demo.py, line 10, in <module>n print t.render(f=f)n   File /usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/jinja2/environment.py, line 969, in rendern return self.environment.handle_exception(exc_info, True)n   File /usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/jinja2/environment.py, line 742, in handle_exceptionn reraise(exc_type, exc_value, tb)n   File <template>, line 1, in top-level template coden AttributeError: 'gi.FunctionInfo' object has no attribute '__call__'nnAfter this patch it producesnn $ ./demo.pyn file:///some/file.txtn file:///some/file.txtnnSigned-off-by: Daniel P. Berrange <berrange@redhat.com>n

Change cache key definitiion in environmentIn 6671b973e6de5abc46829a27fd3bbb989d68ca3a the load_template methodnwas altered to use a cache key other than the template name. The keynchosen was the abs path as returned from the loader get_sourcenmethod. Unless there is no path in which case the name isnused. Unfortunately this introduced a performance regression, #485, asnthe get_source method (in the FileStoreLoader) loads the templaten(causing IO).nnThe purpose of #332 was to allow the loader to change whilst ensuringnthe correct template was loaded, i.e. to fix this casennenv.loader = loader1nenv.get_template('index.html') # return loader1/index.htmlnenv.loader = loader2nenv.get_template('index.html') # also return loader1/index.html because of cachennThis commit changes the cache key to be a tuple of the id(loader) andnthe template name. Therefore fixing the above case without calling thenget_source method and thereby avoiding the IO load.nnA test has been added to ensure the above case works as expected, thisnrequired a minor refactor of the caching tests.n

Change environment cache key constructionChanging from a tuple of the loader ID and template name to a weakrefnto the loader and the template name should avoid situations wherebynthe loader has changed, yet the cached templates are returned. Thisnwould occur if the id of the new loader matches the old. A weakref isnpreferred over a direct reference so that the loader can be garbagedncollected.n

Add test for greater/less than (#624)It can be helpful to have a test for values that are greater or less thanrnanother value, especially when looping over lists and using `select()` orrn`selectattr()` filters. This patch adds tests that allow a developer torncheck if a value is greater or less than another value.rnrnFor example, if I have a list of vehicles and I want to find the motorcycles:rnrnvehicles | selectattr('wheels', 'lessthan', 3)rnrnOr, if I want to find large trucks:rnrnvehicles | selectattr('wheels', 'greaterthan', 4)rnrnTests are included.

Add stricter checking to from ... import ...Currently token parsing on from ... import ... is rather loose u00e2u0080u0094 itnsees the following invalid code as perfectly valid:nn  {% from functions import my_function, %}n  {% from functions import, %}n  {% from functions import %}nnThis is caused by the parser ignoring non-name values where there shouldnbe names, either as the first value or after commas.nnThis commit ensures only name values are allowed as the first value andnany values after commas in the import section.n

Don't skip an erroneous comma when parsing fromCurrently we skip an extra comma when with context is not provided tonthe from statement. This allows invalid code such as this:nn  {% from functions.html import my_function,, %}nnThe primary issue with this is that it is not consistent when providingnwith context. The following code throws an error, contrary to thenprevious example:nn  {% from functions.html import my_function,, with context %}nnIt seems that the comma skipping was originally found in 0611e49 and wasnaccidentally put inside the with context check in ea847c5. It was thennupdated to use skip_if in fdf9530.nnThere doesn't seem to be any reason for this check existing, asndouble commas should never be allowed and serve no purpose in thenstatement.n

More closely match python splatting for callsIn Python, it's legal to use splats in function calls like this:nn  call_function('123', *b, c=5, **d)nnPrior to this change, jinja2 did not allow that. It mandated that allnsplatting had to take place at the end of the call:nn  call_function('123', c=5, *b, **d)nnThis commit allows both orders.nnAdditionally, this commit adds tests for more things that are illegal:nnamely giving a function a positional argument after using a splat tonunpack positional arguments or giving a function a named argument afternusing a double splat to unpack keyword arguments.n

Fix broken nl2br filter exampleThis example attempts to handle both Windows-style and Unix-style line endings, but does it wrong; as noted at https://stackoverflow.com/q/12521127/1709587, the regex here will match a single rn as if it were a double line-break, which results in all single Windows-style line-breaks getting converted into

breaks instead of
breaks as intended.nnThis patch fixes that by applying Alan Moore's proposed fix from https://stackoverflow.com/a/12521544/1709587 of using a negative lookahead so that a r cannot be counted as a line break if it is followed by a n (while still allowing the rn combination to count as a line break).n
